lines.text: SATURDAY, APRIL 30, 1983
Washington Ballroom 7:30-10 PM
Symposium: The Regulation of Energy Balance in Humanst
Edward S Horton, Chairman
Welcome. HH Sandstead, President, American Society for Clinical Nutrition.
Introduction. An overview of the assessment and regulation of energy balance
n humans. Edward S Horton, Burlington, VT.
Physiology of the control of intake. Theodore B Van Itallie, New York, NY.
Long-term measurements of energy balance in humans using a respiration
chamber. Eric Jequier, Lausanne, Switzerland.
Measurement of energy expenditure in humans by the doubly-labeled water
method. Dale A Schoeller, Chicago, IL.
The role of thyroid hormones and insulin in the regulation of energy metabo-
lism. Elliot Danforth, Jr, Burlington, VT.
The role of the sympathetic nervous system and catecholamines in the regula-
tion of energy metabolism. Lewis Landsberg, Boston, MA.
Discussion.
GETTING AROUND IN DC
When you check into the Sheraton Washington Hotel (or,
if staying at another hotel, and arrive at the Sheraton for
Look for me . . .
ASCN sessions), ask for a Sheraton Pathfinder at the Regis-
For information on the Journal
tration Desk of the Hotel. This will really help you find your
way around.
Session Rooms
The Washington Ballroom (all ASCN slide sessions) is
number 33 on the map, lobby level; Maryland Suite (all
ASCN poster sessions) is number 22 (23, 24 and 25 com-
bined) on the lobby level; the Early Lights (Saturday
Brunch) is number 40, first level.
Jogging Path
Joggers may wish to continue jogging while away from
home by using the Perrier Parcourse Circuit which is about
3/8 of a mile from the hotel. Exit through the Park Tower
lobby, turn left down Calvert Street, one block to 24th
Street, cross Calvert, go down into the park and watch for
the fitness trail starting point.
Tip Guide
Tipping depends on t
nds on the quality of service you receive. For
excellent service you might give additional consideration;
and, likewise, poor service may cause you to reevaluate the
traditional tip. A few guidelines are:
Cab driver, 15% of bill; if small fare, increase percentage.
Bellman, from 50c to $1 a bag; if you have a lot of baggage
and the bellman uses a dolly, the 50c per bag figure is
reasonable.
Waiters/ Waitresses, 15% of the bill - excluding tax.
Chambermaid, 50c per day is an appreciated gesture.
Bartender, 10 to 15 percent of bar bill, excluding tax,
before you go to the table: 25c per person minimum for one
Albert I. Mendeloff, MD, Editor-in-Chief
drink.
American Journal of Clinical Nutrition
Lunch-counter server, 10 percent of bill, excluding tax,
but never less than 15c. No tip is necessary for coffee or
beverage without food.
Parking Attendant, no tip if a parking fee is charged;
otherwise, $1.00.
